{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9b35aa5b-0537-4023-b16d-df13f2920aba","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes, the OS automatically generates a crash report. You can find it in:\n\n**Crash Reports:**\n- `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (user apps)\n- `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (system-wide)\n\nFiles are named like `YourApp_<date>_<machine>.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS).\n\n**To view:**\n```bash\n# List recent reports\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/ | head\n\n# Or open Console.app → Crash Reports\nopen -a Console\n```\n\n**Core dumps** (if you need a full memory dump):\n```bash\n# Enable core dumps before running\nulimit -c unlimited\n# Cores land in /cores/core.<pid>\n```\n\nNote: SIP may prevent core dump generation on newer macOS. You can disable it in recovery mode, but the `.ips` crash reports are usually sufficient for stack traces and fault addresses.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"949e249c-02ec-4e14-90af-20e0c5b82b4c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to find crash dumps or crash reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` is not available. This is a knowledge question about macOS crash reporting mechanisms. Let me answer directly from my knowledge.","outputTokens":315,"requestId":"C96F:35A1EF:1DE3F33:212B2C0:6A0529C0"},"id":"345d9521-a234-4da4-ac86-e86b1b7379bc","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:47:53.437Z","parentId":"dfb5125a-dad7-4784-af35-4a11767139bd"}
